 *1357292389*Diary of playing ita-karuta
 This year, I took my wife back to my parents' house in Osaka. When I told my wife about this, she said, "The kids play dominoes with the Hyakunin Isshu," and I was like, "What the heck is this? I told my wife that in her home country, Hokkaido, the Hyakunin Isshu is made of wood. <a href="http://www.amazon.co.jp/gp/product/B001CIKHAW/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&tag=nishiohirokaz-22&linkCode=as2&camp=247&creative =7399&creativeASIN=B001CIKHAW">Hyakunin Isshu: A Poem by One Hundred Poets, Playing on a Board</a>.
 
 I searched Amazon and found it for sale, so I bought it right away. The handle is made of wood, and it looks like I can topple dominoes with it.
 
 The characters written on the tag also use <a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%A4%89%E4%BD%93%E4%BB%AE%E5%90%8D'>variant forms of kana</a>, which are no longer taught in elementary schools due to the 1900 revision of the Ordinance for Enforcement of the Elementary School Ordinance. </a> which is no longer taught in elementary schools due to the revision of the Enforcement Regulations for Elementary School Ordinances in 1900. I thought it would be impossible to actually play with it, but when I showed it to my aunt and uncle, they got very excited and said, "It's fun, let's play with it. When I played with it, I found that it played more decently than I had imagined.
 
 [f:id:nishiohirokazu:20130104183916p:image]
 
 My aunt and uncle's generation, who are around 60 years old, must have already been around 50 years since they were no longer taught in elementary school, but they seem to be able to read it surprisingly well. Their grandparents were of the generation that normally read and wrote in this script, so perhaps things written in this script were still easily visible to them. For me, the third generation who was not taught this script, it has become something that is only "rarely seen on billboards. It seems that by the time my children's generation comes along, even the signs will be gone. I don't think I'll have a chance to know that they exist.
 
 This year I spent my New Year's break thinking about the rise and fall of culture.
 
