 *1357305321*Theory of Inventive Problem Solving in IT
 The Theory of Inventive Problem Solving (<a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRIZ'>TRIZ</a>) is a methodology that tries to make inventions more efficient by "searching for similar problems and their solutions in a database of existing inventions," rather than relying on "inspiration. This methodology is called "TRIZ" (< href='href='_95'>TRIZ</a>).
 
 Simply explained, the problem to be solved is expressed as a "contradiction in characteristics" such as "increase in strength but not in weight. The system then searches for existing patent information that solves the same problem and uses it as a reference. There are auxiliary systems such as the "contradiction matrix," which classifies characteristics into 39 categories and examines 40 typical patterns of solutions from a 39x39 matrix.
 
 However, because of its age (1946-1969), it lacks characteristics related to the information technology that has developed since then. Things like disk capacity and line speed are not on the list of attributes. Can we consider disk capacity as equivalent to "volume"? What does line speed correspond to?
 
 That is why I thought it would be beneficial to re-categorize existing "solution methods" by what contradiction they were trying to solve and what they were trying to improve at the expense of what. For example, a method to solve the problem of insufficient storage capacity at the expense of completeness of information would be to use lossy compression such as JPEG or <a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%96%E3%83%AB%E3%83%BC%E3%83%A0%E3 %83%95%E3%82%A3%E3%83%AB%E3%82%BF'>bloom filters</a>.
 
 There's a <a href="http://www.osaka-gu.ac.jp/php/nakagawa/TRIZ/jforum/2007Forum/MishraTextbook/Chapt4J-080204.pdf">previous study</a> that aims to do the same thing. I'm uncomfortable with <a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/ADSL'>ADSL</a> being classified as "asymmetric" along with the design of the mouse pointer and the mouse itself. I don't feel that being called "asymmetry" solves the problem when you have the contradiction of wanting to increase the speed of the line, but increasing the speed reduces reliability. To me this looks like a way to "improve average performance by allocating more resources to things that are used more frequently". It's a companion to the <a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%8F%E3%83%95%E3%83%9E%E3%83%B3%E7%AC%A6%E5%8F%B7'>Huffman code</a>.
 
 When one wants to reduce computation time, one can sacrifice memory space and "compute on typical inputs first". This is akin to prefetching or speculative execution in terms of "doing it first," and caching or memoizing in terms of "sacrificing storage space to save it for later use.
 
